@endnode
@REM --------
@node "Intro"
@title "ViewDiz - Introduction."
ViewDiz is a small utility for viewing and manipulating file descriptions
from a great variety of filetypes. Description-viewing is done via requesters
which makes it perfect for Directory Opus etc.
Viewing is only a small part of ViewDiz; the real power lies in the advanced
CLI-interface that will allow you to do virtually anything with the
description.

List of some features:

  * Easy-to-use, nice-looking GUI (optional)
  * Unlimited filetypes (modular design)
  * Unlimited functions (via wizards)
  * Editing/saving/stripping of File_ID.DIZ
  * Filenote & version support
  * Aminet.readme -> File_ID.DIZ <-> Filenote option
  * 100% configurable filetype-actions (unpacking, viewing etc.)
  * Locale support
  * System friendly (can be made resident)
  * Fast & free!

...And with the included wizards:

  * Clipboard support
  * Advanced Banner options
  * Extended wordwrapper/stripper
  * Interactive-filelist creator
  * DLDchecker support
  * Log files

Filehandling is done via external modules - the list below shows some of
the included modules:

  * Archives:     Lha/Lzh, Lzx, Zip, Arj, Tar, Tgz
  * Packers:      Xfx, Dms, Dsq, Xpk, Exe
  * Text:         Txt/Nfo, Html, Readme, UUe
  * Pictures:     Iff, Jpg, Gif
  * Music:        Mod/Med, Mus (exotic).

@endnode
@REM --------
@node "Descriptions"
@title "ViewDiz - About file descriptions."
File descriptions are small pieces of text that describes the contents of a
file. This may be the name of the program, version number, author, comments
etc. This information can be stored in different ways; below you can see some
of the formats ViewDiz supports:

@{b}@{u}File_id.diz@{ub}@{uu}

Many filetypes (Archives, pictures etc.) allows you to add/extract the
description via a system called "file_id.diz".
"File_id.diz" is just a small textfile that have been added to the mainfile.
Later it can be extracted to give the user a short description of the file.
"File_id.diz" is typically used on bullitin board systems.

@{b}@{u}Aminet Short-description@{ub}@{uu}

Files uploaded to the internet-archive Aminet @{i}always @{ui}comes with a companion
readme-file that contain a singlelined file description of a max. 40 chars.

@{b}@{u}AmigaDOS Filenotes@{ub}@{uu}

ALL files under AmigaDOS can hold a filenote. This note can contain a 80 chars
long file description. It's a very neat way of keeping a description as it can
be viewed directly from CLI (via the C:List command). Unfortunately this note
is lost when uploading to a BBS/Aminet.

@{b}@{u}Version info@{ub}@{uu}

ALL files can contain a @{i}version-string.@{ui} This string tells you the
name, version and date of creation. Sometimes more informations are given.
@endnode
@REM --------
@node "install"
@title "ViewDiz - Installation."
Doubleclick the install icon.

Note: You are advised to install the "ViewDiz-extras.lha" archive to take
advantage of all modules and wizards.
@endnode

@REM --------
@node "requirements"
@title "ViewDiz - Requirements."
To run ViewDiz you will need the following:

  · Classic AmigaOS v38+ (Kickstart 2.1+)
  · Reqtools.library v37+

Also some extra programs are needed depending on which filetypes you wish to
process. Most of these can be found in the "ViewDiz-extras.lha" archive. See
the @{"Modules & Wizards section" link extern} for details.
@endnode

@REM --------
@node "Usage"
@title "ViewDiz - Usage."
@{b}@{u}From CLI:@{ub}@{uu}

  1:>ViewDiz File/A [Arguments]

A window will open with the description (if any) of the chosen file. Also you
will see a range of @{"buttons" link buttons} that'll let you perform certain
actions on the description/file.

@{b}@{u}Arguments:@{ub}@{uu}

None of the below listed arguments are required if you simply want to view
a file description. But try them out, and discover the real power of ViewDiz!

  @{"    To/K    " link "opt_to"}	Save description to a file
  @{"   Edit/S   " link "opt_edit"}	Pop up editor before viewing
  @{"   Kill/S   " link "opt_kill"}	Remove description from file
  @{" Execute/S  " link "opt_execute"}	Run the execution function
  @{"  Wizard/M  " link "opt_wizard"}	Run external wizard(s)
  @{" Keepdiz/T  " link "opt_keepdiz"}	Keep/delete t:file_id.diz
  @{"  Quiet/S   " link "opt_quiet"}	Disable Requesters/User activity

  @{" Autosave/S " link "opt_autosave"}	Save description automatically
  @{" Savenote/S " link "opt_savenote"}	Save to filenote

  @{"Uppercase/S " link "opt_uppercase"}	Convert description to uppercase
  @{"Lowercase/S " link "opt_uppercase"}	Convert description to lowercase

  @{"   Font/K   " link "opt_font"}	Select font (name.font)
  @{"Fontsize/K/N" link "opt_fontsize"}	Select fontsize
  @{" Pubscreen/K" link "opt_pubscreen"}	Select Public screen

  /A = Required   /S = Switch   /K = Keyword
  /N = Number     /M = Multi    /T = Toggle (ON/OFF)

Advanced users may want to have a look at the @{"program flowsheet" link flowsheet} to see in
which order the options are executed.
@endnode

@REM --------
@node "Configuration"
@title "ViewDiz - Configuration"
A special drawer, "Env:ViewDiz/", is used to store external files. This is
a short examination of the various files:

.modules   Heart of the file recognition! Contain info about all the filetypes
           available.

.editor    Script executed when you press "EDIT". It's important that the used
           editor @{i}do not detatch@{ui} itself from CLI. CygnusED do this if
           it's not started with the "-Keepio" or "-sticky" option.

.tabu	   When using the @{"savenote" link "opt_savenote"} option the description will
           be saved in the filenote. Before this ViewDiz will strip the
           description for some unimportant chars. These chars are specified
           here.

Modules/   Drawer where the external filetype-modules are stored.

Wizards/   Drawer in which the socalled @{"Wizards" link "opt_wizard"} are stored.
@endnode

@REM --------
@node developer
@Title "ViewDiz - Developer"
This section is for developers who what to add a new filetype to ViewDiz. You
do not need to be an expert in Amiga programming to do this, but you will need
some skills in AmigaDOS, though.

To add a filetype you must do two things:

  1. Create a module.
  2. Tell ViewDiz about it.

@{b}@{u}1. Modules:@{ub}@{uu}

The filetype system of is modular: Each filetype has got it's own external
module to take care of description extraction, saving, deleting etc. In this
way an unlimited amount of filetypes can be added.

Modules are special AmigaDOS-scripts, launched by ViewDiz. Via arguments it
will get 3 inputs:

  1) Filename with full path.
  2) A command.
  3) Filename of the description.

A template file is available in "ViewDiz-extras.lha". Also having a look at
the premade modules, should give you an idea how to do it.
You are welcome to improve/fix the current modules - if so please mail them
to me, and I will include them in the next release.

@{b}@{u}2. Configfile:@{ub}@{uu}

When you have created your module you must tell ViewDiz some of it's
capabilities. This is done in "Env:ViewDiz/.modules".

This is a textfile with one line per filetype - each line must obey the
following template:

  MODULE/A,FLAGS/A,ITEM/A/N,DEFAULT/A,PATTERN/A,FILETYPE/A

  MODULE/A   Full path of the module

  FLAGS/A    Flags that specify the properties of the module. What can it do ?

             R = Read a file description
             W = Write a file description
             E = Use a special editor
             X = Perform an action on the file (play, view, etc...)
             D = Delete file description

  ITEM/A/N   If the "X"-flag (see above) is set, the user will be able to push
             a button and the action is executed. The button-text can be
             fetched from the localized "viewdiz.catalog" by stating which
             string number (item) you wish to use. If you want to add an item
             to the catalog, you can contact me and I'll reserve one for you.

  DEFAULT/A  If the ITEM/A/N failed (no catalog or invalid item) the text
             specified here will be used. You can force ViewDiz to use this
             by setting the ITEM/A/N to zero.

  PATTERN/A  Filetypes are recognized via filenames. This specifies which
             pattern to match. (Standard AmigaDOS notation)

  FILETYPE/A Name of the filetype.

Important:

  · Arguments with spaces must be enclosed with double-quotes (").
  · Double-quotes within an argument may be set with *"
  · Empty arguments are NOT allowed - use 2 double-qoutes ("")
@endnode
@REM --------
@node flowsheet
@Title "ViewDiz - Flowsheet"
The following is a program-flowsheet that illustartes in which order various
functions and arguments are handled.

- Check xpk status.
  > set "xpkstatus" local variable.
- Get filetype
  > Read config file.
  > Binary check.
- Extract description.
  > "module CMD=Read".
  > filenote.
  > version info.
- Trim description.

- Run Wizards
- Uppercase/S
- Lowercase/S
- Edit/S
  > "viewdiz/editor.s" OR "module CMD=Edit"
- Autosave/S
  > Savenote/S
  > "module CMD=WRITE"
- To/K
- Execute/S
  > "module CMD=Execute"
- Kill/S
  > "module CMD=Delete"

- Reqtools Requester (View description!)
  > View description
    > Button: Edit
      > "viewdiz/editor.s" OR "module CMD=Edit"
      > Save/Cancel requester
        > Button: Save
          > Savenote/S => Save to filenote
          > "module CMD=Save"
        > Cancel: Don't save changes.
    > Button: Execute => "module CMD=Execute"
    > Button: Quit => Quit viewdiz
- Keepdiz/T=OFF
  > Delete T:File_ID.diz
- CleanUp & Exit
@endnode

@REM --------
@node buttons
@Title "ViewDiz - Buttons"
ViewDiz have got three buildin, localized buttons:

  `Edit'	Edit description.
  `Save'	Save description.
  `Quit'	Quit ViewDiz.

Besides these you will encounter other buttons depending on which filetype you
are processing, for example:

  `Extract'	Extract files in archive
  `View'	View picture
  `Play'	Play music file.
  ...etc
@endnode

@REM --------
@node opt_keepdiz
@Title "ViewDiz - Keepdiz"
@{b}Keepdiz=KD/T:@{ub}

Keeps the "t:file_id.diz" file after ViewDiz terminates, default is ON.

  1> ViewDiz myfile.lha keepdiz=OFF
@endnode
@REM --------

@node opt_Execute
@Title "ViewDiz - Execute"
@{b}Execute=EX/S:@{ub}

Tries to start the EXECUTE function in the filetype-module. For example:

  1:> Viewdiz myfile.lha execute quiet
  - will bring up a requester, asking where to unpack myfile.lha to. Select,
    and the archive will be unpacked - no further useractivity.

@endnode

@REM --------
@node opt_kill
@Title "ViewDiz - Kill"
@{b}Kill/S:@{ub}

Tries to delete the description from the file, using the DELETE function in
the filetype-module.

  1:> Viewdiz myfile.lha kill
  - will remove (if any) the file_id.diz stored inside the LHa-archive, THEN
    the description will be shown in the window.
@endnode


@REM --------
@node opt_uppercase
@Title "ViewDiz - Uppercase"
@{b}Uppercase=UC/S:@{ub}

Converts description to uppercase. Note that the converted description will
NOT be saved automatically - to do that you must use the autosave, for
example:

  1:> ViewDiz myfile.lha uppercase autosave

@{b}Lowercase=LC/S:@{ub}

If you prefer lowercase...
@endnode

@REM --------
@node "opt_Edit"
@Title "ViewDiz - Edit"
@{b}Edit=ED/S:@{ub}

Popup the editor before the description is viewed. It is especially usefull
in combination with the "Quiet" option:

  1:> ViewDiz myfile.lha edit autosave quiet
  - will automatically start your editor with the found description. When the
    editor is closed, the desciption will be saved without any useractivity.
@endnode

@REM --------
@node "opt_Autosave"
@Title "ViewDiz - Autosave"
@{b}Autosave=AS/S:@{ub}

Saves the description without useractivity. If used with the @{"Savenote/S" link opt_savenote} switch
the description will be saved in the filenote.
@endnode

@REM --------
@node "opt_Savenote"
@Title "ViewDiz - Savenote"
@{b}Savenote=SN/S:@{ub}

Force description to be saved to filenote. Affects @{"Autosave/S" link opt_autosave} and the "Save"
botton. Chars stated in the "Env:ViewDiz/.tabu" will be filtered out, so the
description will fit better to the 80 chars allowed in a filenote.

Myfile.lha is thought to contain a File_id.diz description:

  1:> viewdiz myfile.lha savenote
  - editing and saving the description will envolve the filenote only.

  1:> viewdiz myfile.lha savenote quiet
  - automatically save the found description to filenote.

  1:> viewdiz myfile.lha autosave savenote 
  - save desc. to filenote, then show description.
@endnode

@REM --------
@node "opt_To"
@Title "ViewDiz - To"
@{b}To/K:@{ub}

Saves the description to a file. Example:

  1:> viewdiz myfile to ram:my_description
  - will show the description as normal, but also save it to
    ram:my_description.

You can also use this funtion to print the description to the screen or your
printer:

  1:> viewdiz myfile to * quiet		( » window )
  1:> viewdiz myfile to con: q		( » new window )
  1:> viewdiz myfile to prt: q		( » printer )

Tip: To add an extra linefeed after the last line you could do this:

 1:> echo "`viewdiz myfile to * q`"
@endnode
@REM --------
@node "opt_quiet"
@Title "ViewDiz - Quiet"
@{b}Quiet=Q/S:@{ub}

Suppress requesters - no useractivity. For example:

  1:> viewdiz myfile quiet
  - will extract the description (if any) a place if in t:file_id.diz.

  1:> viewdiz myfile.lha kill quiet
  - will remove any description found in myfile.lha without any useractivity.
@endnode
@REM --------
@node "opt_Pubscreen"
@Title "ViewDiz - Pubscreen"
@{b}Pubscreen=PS/K:@{ub}

Specifies public-screen for ViewDiz' window. Remember that public screen names
are @{i}case sensitive.@{ui}

  1:> viewdiz myfile pubscreen MY_Pubscreen
  - If "MY_Pubscreen" isn't found ViewDiz will open on the screen from which
    it was launched.
@endnode
@REM --------
@node "opt_Font"
@Title "ViewDiz - Font"
@{b}Font=F/K:@{ub}

Specifies font used by the ViewDiz requester, for example:

  1:> viewdiz myfile font=xen.font

Many file_id.diz files contain ANSI graphics, so it is advised that you use a
non-proportional font.

See also @{"Fontsize/N" link opt_fontsize}

@endnode

@REM --------
@node "opt_Fontsize"
@Title "ViewDiz - Fontsize"
@{b}Fontsize=FS/K/N:@{ub}

Specifies fontsize:

  1:> viewdiz myfile fontsize=20
@endnode

@REM --------
@node "opt_Wizard"
@Title "ViewDiz - Wizard"
@{b}Wizard=WZ/M:@{ub}

Run external "wizards". Wizards are small modules that can do something with
the obtained description/file and is placed in the Env:ViewDiz/Wizards drawer.

One of the included wizards is called "Log" and will create a list of the
files you have processed with ViewDiz:

  1:> viewdiz myfile.lha Wizard="Log"

See the @{"modules & wizards section" link extern} for a description of all available
wizards. The "Wizard" keyword is not required and you can specify an unlimited
number of wizards, for example:

  1:> viewdiz myfile.lha "log" "clip" "wrap width=20"

Important thing about Wizards:

  · Wizards are execute in the order they are typed.
  · Wizards doesn't autosave your description - Use the Autosave/S argument.
  · Always place wizards at the end of the argument line.
  · Double-quotes (") inside wizard arguments must have a star (*) prefix:

    viewdiz myfile.lha "banner banner=*"Ram Disk:text*""
@endnode

@REM --------
@node "History"
@Title "ViewDiz - History & Future"

2.1	08-Oct-98
	· Complete rewrite. No more Arexx --> faster, shorter, better!
	· Support for wizards; programs that can do certain things with the
	  description while ViewDiz is running.
	· New filetypes: Mpeg3, TarGZ, Exe
	· New arguments: Wizard/M, Lowercase/K, Execute/S, Autosave/S,
	  Keepdiz/T
	· Removed or renamed arguments:
	  List/K, Noreq/S, Extdiz/S, Flushlibs/S, Maxduplet/S,
	  Clip/S, From/K, Killdiz/K, Upperdiz/S
	· Several enhancements to the filetypes.
	· Program flowsheet.
	· External programs now in separate archive: ViewDiz-Extras.lha
	· Installer script made much shorter and simpler.
	· Possible to use a different editor for different filetypes.

2.0	18-Mar-98
	· Major change: Filetype system completely rewritten - Modular design
	  ensures unlimited number of filetypes (User defined).
	· New options: Delreadme/S, Upperdiz/S, Killdiz/S
	· Added hungarian catalog.
	· Cleans up the T: drawer after Lha-readme processing (Better late
	  than never...Thanks Fabio!)
	· Safer Lha/Lzx handling.
	· Autodetect Eagleplayer2/Delitracker2 working directory.
	· Registrationform generator included.
	· Homepage!
	· Documentation layout change.

1.9	17-Oct-97
	· Locale support.
	· NEW options: Add/K, Edit/S, Flushlibs/S, List/K, MaxDuplet/N
	· File_id.diz on ARJ, XPK, xFX (packed), MOD/MED (unpacked).
	· xFX unpacking using either CLI-command or ARexx-port.
	· More error trapping.
	· Improved CLI-template.
	· Installer-script: DOpus5+ view/read/play functions now supported,
	  more checks added + some minor improvements.
	· Viewdiz.small image added for DOpus5 users.
	· Removed "Winshots" + documentation for external commands.
	  (Took up too much diskspace)
	· ENV:ViewDiz/DMSdest renamed to "DevDest".
	· HELP-button errormsg fixed.
	· Binary Lha/HTML check fixed.

1.8	06-Sep-97
	· DiskSqueeze support (Read/Write of File_ID.DIZ).
	· NEW options: Pubscreen/K, Font/K, From/K, SaveDIZ/S.
	· DMS drives selected via configfile.
	· Music prefixes selected via configfile.
	· Hippoplayer, AModPlay & Multiplayer ARexx support added.
	· Description now scrolled in Eagleplayer window.
	· "Forbidden chars" used by "Savenote" selected via configfile.
	· "NoREQ" option now works with "Savenote" too.
	· Unpack-button for XPK- and Powerpacked datafiles.
	· Directory Opus buttons included.
	· Install script rewritten (Using the standard Installer)
	  now containing full configuration part ...brrr a tough and dirty job!
	· Configuration system completely rewritten - User defined programs now
	  started via scripts -> 100% configurable!
	· Now uses rexxdossupport.library to improve functionality.
	· Argument handling completely rewritten - Works much more prof.
	  - Save option now supports spaces in destination file.
	· Improved documentation (I hope :^)
	· Newer version of MagicDIZ included, v2.05 --> v2.06
	· Improved errorhandling.
	· Binary MED-recognition added.
	· Binary THX-recognition didn't work --> Fixed!
	· Wrong .Readme code stole precious CPU/DISK-time! --> Fixed!
	  Also Readme's are now searched in arc-subdirectories too.
	· Lots of code cleanups and optimizations, again! :^)

1.7	27-Jul-97
	· SAVENOTE-option added - Saves file_id.diz in filecomment.
	· CLIP-option added - Copies file_id to clipboards.
	· SAVE-option added - Copies file_id to a file.
	· NOREQ-option added - a sort of 'quiet' mode.
	· Custom Texteditor via configfile.
	· External TXT-extracter now used - Welcome to TEXTract !
	  Textfiles larger than 65k now supported.
	· File_ID.diz support for guide-files removed due to TEXTract.
	· Binary filetype-check on textfiles to avoid adding File_ID.DIZ
	  to packed files.
	· Filename no longer need to contain full path.
	· New design of the help-window.
	· Max. linelength changed from 40 to 44 (file_id.diz "standart").
	· Bugfix in picture recognition -> Major speed increasement!
	· Small improvements made on several routines.

1.6	08-Jul-97
	· File_ID.DIZ edit/saving for GIF,IFF,JPG,Textfiles.
	· Filenote edit/saving for unknown filetypes.
	· View/Play option for pics/music/text - Including an easy and
          fast configfile for customizing the viewer/player.
	· Direct ARexx-support for Delitracker/Eagleplayer.
	· Aminet .readme file now searched in LHa archive too.
	· Description splitting if longer than 40 chars (word orientated).
	· Installation script included.
	· Documentation now in AmigaGuide format.
	· Minor bug removed in aminet.readme processing.
	· Bug removed in TXT/HTML processing - These are now being searched.
          for .readme/filenote & version info too.
	· Optimized the code for speed.

1.5	01-Jul-97
	· Aminet .readme support.
	· HTML Title-support.
	· DMS Editing and Extracting.
	· Full ZIP support.
	· Version search added.
	· Binary filetype-check on unknown suffixes.
	· DMS processing made faster (Now using DMSdescript).
	· Optimized disk routines for speed.
	· Fixed a bug when processing LZx files.
	· Source no longer included because of unauthorized clones.

1.4	05-Jun-97
	· Added my own file_id.diz extracting routine; this results in some
	  slower DMS-processing, but spaces in filenames are now allowed.
          GIF,ARJ & ZIP files can't be extracted now (Who cares anyway??)
	· Uses filenote-info if no file_id.diz is found
	· Fixed a bug when editing file_id.diz in LZx-files

1.31	20-May-97
	· First puplic release.

@{b}FUTURE:@{ub}

2.x	xx-xxx-xx
	· Viewdiz.library (incl. autodocs)
	  I'm currently working on this and it will be more efficient than
	  the current code. Furthermore it will enable other programmers
	  to take advantage of the external module/wizard system.

	· Multifile support
	  An old lack which will soon become history!

	· GUI prefs program
	  I have been working on this for some time now, and it will be
	  font-sensitive, resizeable & non-MUI.

	· Run multiple ViewDiz tasks

	· Executable modules/wizards. This will allow frequently used modules
	  or wizards to be pre-loaded and hence speed things up.

@{b}CURRENT RESTRICTIONS:@{ub}

Multiple copies of ViewDiz can't be run at the same time, as the filetype
modules are usign "t:file_id.diz" for description storage. This will be
changed in the next version.

@endnode
